{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c5f86419-33ae-4b4c-ac00-b637926f441a","content":"In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance **per HTTP request** — the request defines the scope boundary. In MAUI, **there are no HTTP requests**, so there's no natural scope boundary. `AddScoped` effectively behaves like `AddSingleton`, giving you the same `DbContext` instance for the entire app lifetime.\n\n**Fixes:**\n\n1. **Use `AddTransient`** — gives a new `DbContext` per injection. Simplest fix.\n2. **Create scopes manually** with `IServiceScopeFactory`:\n   ```csharp\n   using var scope = scopeFactory.CreateScope();\n   var db = scope.ServiceProvider.GetRequiredService<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n3. **Use `DbContextFactory`** (recommended for MAUI/Blazor):\n   ```csharp\n   // Registration\n   builder.Services.AddDbContextFactory<MyDbContext>(opts =>\n       opts.UseSqlite(\"...\"));\n\n   // Usage\n   using var db = dbContextFactory.CreateDbContext();\n   ```\n\n`AddDbContextFactory` is the idiomatic approach — it gives you explicit lifetime control and avoids the stale-data and concurrency issues that a long-lived `DbContext` causes.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b662cbef-38d5-4276-a910-db8851c24e38","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a common pitfall when migrating from ASP.NET Core to .NET MAUI regarding dependency injection scoping, specifically with `AddScoped` and `DbContext`. This is a conceptual question I can answer directly without needing to search any codebase.\n\nThe key issue: In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance per HTTP request. In MAUI, there's no concept of an HTTP request scope — so `AddScoped` behaves essentially like `AddSingleton`, meaning the same DbContext instance lives for the entire app lifetime.","outputTokens":441,"requestId":"F3C1:1A8A2F:1F5D286:233BF7A:69E81C06"},"id":"e362a542-48f7-44a4-a6eb-7ebf499b36c4","timestamp":"2026-04-22T00:53:36.314Z","parentId":"d20eac46-b9d1-44c0-8d2f-6c57cc50f80c"}
